● Important context — I'm running on an Arch box, not on wisp itself.
  /proc/cmdline here is the Arch host, the MT7925 PCI path doesn't exist, and
  pstore is empty. So I can't pull the new dump from here.

  What we know now:

  - Test A failed. D0 pin on 0000:c1:00.0 was supposed to block
  mt792x_pm_wake_work from ever running. It crashed anyway.
  - That falsifies "WiFi runtime-PM wake is the sole trigger" — if the pin
  actually took effect at boot.

  Two ways to interpret the failure, and they want different next steps:

  1. D0 pin took effect, system still crashed → the wake path isn't the trigger;
   mt76 RX corruption is happening on a different code path (steady-state RX,
  not wake-from-sleep). Test B (pcie_aspm=off) is still worth running, but if it
   also fails the producer hypothesis (mt76) needs to start including non-wake
  paths.
  2. D0 pin didn't take effect → tmpfiles ran too early / udev rule didn't match
   / wrong PCI address on this revision. Then we haven't really tested the
  hypothesis.

  Before I edit the config to move to Test B, can you paste from wisp:

  cat /proc/cmdline
  cat /sys/bus/pci/devices/0000:c1:00.0/power/control
  sudo ls -lat /var/lib/systemd/pstore/ | head -10

  And the new pstore dump (001/dmesg.txt from the newest dir under
  /var/lib/systemd/pstore/). The call trace is the deciding evidence — if it's
  still mt792x_pm_wake_work → mt76_dma_rx_cleanup, the D0 pin didn't hold. If
  it's a different mt76 path (or something unrelated), interpretation 1 is right
   and we have new information.

