● Test A actually changed the failure signature — that's important data. The new
   oops is not the mt76 page_pool/wake-path crash from round 7. It's a different
   producer that was being preempted by the wake-path bug.

  What changed

  ┌───────────┬──────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────┐
  │           │   Round 7 (no D0 pin)    │      Round 8 (D0 pin held)      │
  ├───────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Uptime to │ 312s                     │ 338s                            │
  │  crash    │                          │                                 │
  ├───────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Detector  │ panic_on_warn on         │ slub_debug redzone check        │
  │           │ pp_magic mismatch        │                                 │
  ├───────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Site      │ mt76_dma_rx_cleanup from │ nd_alloc_stack/pick_link        │
  │           │  mt792x_pm_wake_work     │ (random VFS allocation)         │
  ├───────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Victim    │ page_pool netmem         │ kmalloc-2k right redzone,       │
  │           │                          │ 8-byte overwrite past freed obj │
  ├───────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Bytes     │ corrupted pp_magic       │ 72 1b 90 27 4f a3 19 04         │
  └───────────┴──────────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────┘

  /sys/bus/pci/devices/0000:c1:00.0/power/control = on and the kernel cmdline is
   right, so the D0 pin took effect. With the WiFi runtime-PM wake path blocked,
   the system survived ~6 seconds longer — and then crashed on a different
  corruption pattern. Same mt7925 modules loaded, same amdgpu loaded, same
  pinctrl_amdisp/i2c_designware_amdisp (which the historical PASS/FAIL pinned as
   part of the FAIL set) loaded.

  What that means

  - Round 7's hypothesis "the runtime-PM wake handler is the trigger" is partly
  falsified: the wake handler was one code path through which mt76 (or an
  adjacent driver) was hitting bad memory, but it isn't the sole producer. With
  it gone, a different victim shows up.
  - The corruption is happening in steady state, not just at wake. That's new
  and more useful.
  - Detector is on the consumer side (someone else's kmalloc(2K) lands on a slab
   whose previous resident's right redzone got smashed). The producer is whoever
   wrote those 8 bytes past the end of a freed 2K allocation. mt76 RX skbuffs in
   the 2K range are a plausible candidate; amdgpu/amd_pmf surfaces are another.

  Proposal — keep D0 pin, layer Test B on top

  Round 7's plan said "if A fails, revert A and run B." I'd revise: keep A, add 
  B. Reasoning: A demonstrably suppressed one failure path, so reverting it just
   makes round-9 noisier. Layer them.

  Concretely, in hosts/wisp/configuration.nix:
  - Keep the tmpfiles + udev D0-pin rules
  - Add "pcie_aspm=off" to boot.kernelParams

  This rules out PCIe L1 entry/exit as the DMA-corruption trigger while keeping
  the wake-path neutralization. If round 9 is clean, we peel D0 pin first to see
   whether ASPM-off alone is sufficient. If round 9 crashes again, we move to
  Test C (pin amdgpu DPM) — also kept on top of A+B.

  Want me to:

  1. Create the round-8 session dir, save this oops + findings + actions, and
  apply Test B on top of A?
  2. Or first hear pushback / a different direction (e.g., shortcut to
  module_blacklist=mt7925e,mt7925_common and lose WiFi to confirm mt76 is the
  producer)?

