❯ What is pcie_aspm, and what could be some negative sideeffects of having it   
  disabled?                                                                     

● What pcie_aspm is

  PCIe ASPM = Active State Power Management. It's a PCIe link-level power-saving
   feature defined in the PCIe spec. Each PCIe link (CPU/root-complex ↔
  endpoint) can be in one of:

  - L0 — fully active, both directions transmitting.
  - L0s — one direction idle, low-latency exit (~ns).
  - L1 — both directions idle, deeper savings, slower exit (~µs).
  - L1.1 / L1.2 ("L1 substates") — even deeper, with reference clock and/or
  common-mode voltage off; exit on the order of tens of µs to a few ms.

  The hardware autonomously moves between L0/L0s/L1/L1.x when traffic is idle,
  then back to L0 on demand. The Linux pcie_aspm kernel parameter controls
  policy:

  - pcie_aspm=default — follow firmware/ACPI hints
  - pcie_aspm=force — enable ASPM regardless of what firmware says
  - pcie_aspm=off — disable ASPM globally; all links stay at L0
  - (related: pcie_aspm.policy=performance|powersave|powersupersave)

  pcie_aspm=off doesn't disable PCIe runtime D-states (D3hot, D3cold) or the
  device-side runtime PM — those are independent. It only forbids the link-state
   transitions.

  Why we're toggling it for this bug

  L1/L1.x exit on AMD platforms (Ryzen/Strix) has historically been a frequent
  source of races with in-flight DMA: a device de-asserts CLKREQ#, the link
  starts entering L1, then a late DMA scheduling pokes it. On poorly-tuned
  silicon or buggy endpoints this can corrupt a few bytes — exactly the shape of
   round 8's 8-byte right-redzone overwrite. So pcie_aspm=off is a clean way to
  remove that variable from the experiment.

  Negative side-effects of pcie_aspm=off

  Trading off power for stability. On a laptop, the costs land in roughly this
  order of impact:

  1. Battery life regression — biggest hit. ASPM is one of the heavier-weight
  knobs in the platform's power budget on modern laptops. Real-world impact on
  idle/light-load battery is typically 5–25% depending on the system; on Strix
  Halo with a lot of PCIe-attached IP (NVMe, WiFi, iGPU root ports, USB
  controllers, Thunderbolt), expect to feel it. Idle wattage measured via
  powertop / intel_pstate-equivalent will rise visibly.
  2. Higher idle temperature / fan ramp. Links staying in L0 means the SerDes /
  PHYs draw their full active power continuously. Modest CPU-package and
  skin-temp delta — usually a few °C, occasionally enough to nudge the fan curve
   up a notch.
  3. Worse deep-sleep behavior. ASPM L1.x is part of how the platform reaches
  its lowest package C-states (PC8/PC10) and thus the lowest "modern standby" /
  s2idle floors. With ASPM off, the SoC can be held out of the deepest residency
   states — measurable on cpupower idle-info and by observing higher s2idle
  drain. Suspend-to-RAM still works, but s2idle "lid closed in a bag overnight"
  will drain faster.
  4. No correctness regressions on healthy hardware. Throughput, latency,
  interrupt rate — all unaffected (and link latency is nominally better since
  you skip exit cost). You will not lose features, devices will not enumerate
  differently, and nothing should fail to work; this is purely "device runs
  hotter and uses more power."
  5. Specific to this bug: if pcie_aspm=off fixes the corruption, that's
  diagnostic value but it's also a heavy hammer. Two more-targeted options exist
   as future refinements:
    - pcie_aspm.policy=performance — keeps ASPM available but biases toward L0
  unless idle is sustained.
    - Per-device disable via sysfs (/sys/bus/pci/devices/.../link/l1_aspm etc.)
  — disable just on the offending endpoint(s).

  We're using the global form for now because it's the cleanest diagnostic; if
  it works, we can later narrow it to a per-device knob to claw back the battery
   cost.

  For the duration of the test cycle (one boot + a 30-minute soak), the cost is
  negligible. For a long-term mitigation we'd want to scope it down once the
  producer is identified.

